4.17\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 234\n|population_density_km2   =\n|population_density_sq_mi = 2.8\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 214\n|elevation_ft             = 702\n|coordinates              = {{coord|46|03|31|N|85|55|14|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code|ZIP code(s)]]\n|postal_code              = 49836 ([[Germfask Township, Michigan|Germfask]])<br>49840 ([[Doyle Township, Michigan|Gulliver]])<br>49854 ([[Manistique, Michigan|Manistique]])\n|area_code                = [[Area code 906|906]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 26-56060<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1626777<ref>{{gnis|1626777}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Mueller Township''' is a [[civil township]] of [[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. The population was 234 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].\n\n== Communities ==\n* '''Blaney Park''' was established as a lumbering town by the William Mueller Company, a Chicago-based company that operated steam ships on the great lakes.  It was not a successful operation so the town was sold in 1909 to the Wiscon Land and Mining Company, which continued lumbering operations until 1927.  It was then converted into a resort town.{{sfn|Romig|1986|page=66}}\n* '''Port Inland''' is a commercial port in the eastern end of the township at {{Coord|45|58|15|N|85|52|20|W|}}<ref>{{gnis|1617801|Port Inland, Michigan}}</ref> In 2013, it was the 81st [[List of ports in the United States|largest port in the United States]] ranked by tonnage.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the township has a total area of {{convert|87.78|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|83.61|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|4.17|sqmi|sqkm|2}} (4.75%) is water.\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> of 2000, there were 245 people, 102 households, and 84 families residing in the township.  The [[population density]] was 2.9 per square mile (1.1/km\u00b2).  There were 301 housing units at an average density of 3.6 per square mile (1.4/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the township was 88.98% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 8.16% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.63% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.22% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.86% of the population.\n\nThere were 102 households out of which 19.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 75.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 3.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 17.6% were non-families. 14.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 2.62.\n\nIn the township the population was spread out with 18.0% under the age of 18, 3.7% from 18 to 24, 21.2% from 25 to 44, 33.9% from 45 to 64, and 23.3% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 51 years. For every 100 females, there were 118.8 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 107.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the township was $33,571, and the median income for a family was $34,643. Males had a median income of $25,000 versus $21,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the township was $18,507.  About 2.5% of families and 6.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including none of those under the age of eighteen and 10.8% of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Indian Trails]] provides daily intercity bus service via Blaney Park between [[St. Ignace, Michigan|St. Ignace]] and [[Ironwood, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web | title=ST. IGNACE-SAULT STE. MARIE-IRONWOOD | publisher=[[Indian Trails]] | date=January 15, 2013 | accessdate=2013-02-28 | url=http://www.indiantrails.com/sites/default/files/1489_0.pdf | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704084717/http://www.indiantrails.com/sites/default/files/1489_0.pdf | archivedate=July 4, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book |first1=Walter |last1=Romig |title=Michigan Place Names: The History of the Founding and the Naming of More Than Five Thousand Past and Present Michigan Communities |work=Great Lakes Books Series |type=Paperback  |origyear= 1973 |date=October 1, 1986 |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |isbn = 0-8143-1838-X |location=Detroit, Michigan <!--|ISBN=978-0814318386 --> |ref=harv}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Cecilia|url=http://www.miningjournal.net/life/2018/02/blaney-park/|title=Blaney Park; The U.P.\u2019s \u2018premier resort\u2019|website=[[The Mining Journal|Mining Journal]]|date=2018-02-22|access-date=2018-05-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523142849/http://www.miningjournal.net/life/2018/02/blaney-park/|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}\n\n{{Schoolcraft County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Townships in Schoolcraft County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Townships in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mueller_Township,_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Grace, Lady Manners", "text_new": "[[File:Lady-grace-manners-death-mask.jpg|thumb|right|Lady Manners' death mask]]\n[[Image:Lady Manners School.jpg|thumb|right|Lady Manners school]]\n'''Grace, Lady Manners''' (c.1575 \u2013 c.1650) was an [[England|English]] [[noblewoman]] who lived at [[Haddon Hall]] near [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]]. She founded Bakewell's [[Lady Manners School]] in 1636.\n\n==Biography==\nGrace Pierrepont was the daughter of Sir [[Henry Pierrepont (politician)|Henry Pierrepont]], a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter]], and Frances Cavendish.<ref>G.E. Cokayne; with Vicary Gibbs, H.A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, Duncan Warrand and Lord Howard de Walden, editors, The Complete Peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant, Extinct or Dormant, new ed., 13 volumes in 14 (1910-1959; reprint in 6 volumes, Gloucester, U.K.: Alan Sutton Publishing, 2000), volume XI, page 263.</ref> Her maternal grandparents were Sir [[William Cavendish (courtier)|William Cavendish]] and [[Bess of Hardwick]]. Grace's brother was [[Robert Pierrepont, 1st Earl of Kingston-upon-Hull|Robert Pierrepont]], born in 1584, who became the 1st [[Earl of Kingston-upon-Hull]]. Grace's sister, Elizabeth, married [[Thomas Erskine, 1st Earl of Kellie]].\n\nOn 1 August 1593 Grace was married to Sir [[George Manners (died 1623)|George Manners]] (1569-1623) of [[Haddon Hall]] in Derbyshire,  a [[Member of Parliament]].<ref>Mosley, Charles, editor. Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes. Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003. Page 3447</ref> She had nine<ref>per inscription on her husband's monument in Bakewell Church</ref> children, including:\n*[[John Manners, 8th Earl of Rutland]] (1604-1679)<ref>{{cite book|author=Leslie Stephen|title=DNB|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yOEpAAAAYAAJ|year=1893|publisher=Smith, Elder, & Company|page=51}}</ref>\n*Elizabeth Manners, who married [[Robert Sutton, 1st Baron Lexinton]\n*Eleanor Manners, who married [[Lewis Watson, 1st Baron Rockingham]], and had children\n*Frances Manners (died 1652), who married [[Nicholas Saunderson]], 2nd [[Earl Castleton|Viscount Castleton]], and had children\n*Dorothy Manners, who married Sir Thomas Lake\n\nOn 20 May 1636, she founded [[Lady Manners School]] in Bakewell, Derbyshire.<ref>{{cite book|title=Journal of the Derbyshire Archaeological and Natural History Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JnBJAAAAYAAJ|year=1919|publisher=The Society|page=83}}</ref>\n\nHer body is interred in [[Bakewell Parish Church]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Henry Pierrepont (politician)#Family|Family of Henry Pierrepont]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manners, Grace, Lady}}\n[[Category:Founders of educational institutions]]\n[[Category:People from Bakewell]]\n[[Category:17th-century English people]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Pierrepont family|Grace]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n\n\n{{UK-noble-stub}}\n{{England-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Lady-grace-manners-death-mask.jpg|thumb|right|Lady Manners' death mask]]\n[[Image:Lady Manners School.jpg|thumb|right|Lady Manners school]]\n'''Grace, Lady Manners''' (c.1575 \u2013 c.1650) was an [[England|English]] [[noblewoman]] who lived at [[Haddon Hall]] near [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]]. She founded Bakewell's [[Lady Manners School]] in 1636.\n\n==Biography==\nGrace Pierrepont was the daughter of Sir [[Henry Pierrepont (politician)|Henry Pierrepont]], a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter]], and Frances Cavendish.<ref>G.E. Cokayne; with Vicary Gibbs, H.A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, Duncan Warrand and Lord Howard de Walden, editors, The Complete Peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant, Extinct or Dormant, new ed., 13 volumes in 14 (1910-1959; reprint in 6 volumes, Gloucester, U.K.: Alan Sutton Publishing, 2000), volume XI, page 263.</ref> Her maternal grandparents were Rt. Hon. Sir [[William Cavendish (courtier)|William Cavendish]] and [[Bess of Hardwick]]. Grace's brother was [[Robert Pierrepont, 1st Earl of Kingston-upon-Hull|Robert Pierrepont]], born in 1584, who became the 1st [[Earl of Kingston-upon-Hull]]. Grace's sister, Elizabeth, married [[Thomas Erskine, 1st Earl of Kellie]].\n\nOn 1 August 1593 Grace was married to Sir [[George Manners (died 1623)|George Manners]] (1569-1623) of [[Haddon Hall]] in Derbyshire,  a [[Member of Parliament]].<ref>Mosley, Charles, editor. Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes. Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003. Page 3447</ref> She had nine<ref>per inscription on her husband's monument in Bakewell Church</ref> children, including:\n*[[John Manners, 8th Earl of Rutland]] (1604-1679)<ref>{{cite book|author=Leslie Stephen|title=DNB|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yOEpAAAAYAAJ|year=1893|publisher=Smith, Elder, & Company|page=51}}</ref>\n*Elizabeth Manners, who married [[Robert Sutton, 1st Baron Lexinton of Aram]]\n*Eleanor Manners, who married [[Lewis Watson, 1st Baron Rockingham]], and had children\n*Frances Manners (died 1652), who married [[Nicholas Saunderson, 2nd Viscount Castleton]], and had children\n*Dorothy Manners, who married Sir Thomas Lake\n\nOn 20 May 1636, she founded [[Lady Manners School]] in Bakewell, Derbyshire.<ref>{{cite book|title=Journal of the Derbyshire Archaeological and Natural History Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JnBJAAAAYAAJ|year=1919|publisher=The Society|page=83}}</ref>\n\nHer body is interred in [[Bakewell Parish Church]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Henry Pierrepont (politician)#Family|Family of Henry Pierrepont]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manners, Grace, Lady}}\n[[Category:Founders of educational institutions]]\n[[Category:People from Bakewell]]\n[[Category:17th-century English people]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Pierrepont family|Grace]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n\n\n{{UK-noble-stub}}\n{{England-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grace,_Lady_Manners"}
{"title_page": "Towersey Festival", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = Towersey Festival\n| native_name  =\n| logo         = <!--INCLUDE \"[[File:Filename.ext]]\" when entering file name-->\n| logo_caption =\n| image        = Crowd watching The Proclaimers, Towersey 2018.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = Venue 65, Towersey 2018\n| date         = <!--\"dates=\" also works, as merged from\n                 Template:Infobox festival. Do not use both-->\n| begins       =\n| ends         =\n| prev         = \n| next         = \n| frequency    = Annually\n| location     = [[Thame]], Oxfordshire, England\n| years_active =\n| first        = 1965\n| participants =\n| attendance   = c. 10,000\n| genre        =\n| budget       =\n| patron       =\n| organised    = <!--\"organised=\" also works-->\n| website      = {{URL|towerseyfestival.com/}}\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Towersey Festival''' is an annual festival of [[folk music|folk]], [[world music]] and [[traditional dance]], previously held in the village of [[Towersey]], now relocated <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.towerseyvillage.co.uk/about-towersey-village/history/festival/|title=Towersey Festival \u2013 Towersey Village|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref> to neighbouring [[Thame]] in Oxfordshire, England. It has taken place every August [[bank holiday]] weekend since its founding in 1965.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Towersey_music_festival_(4)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1671760.jpg|thumb|right|Festivalgoers at Towersey Festival 2006]]\n\nThe festival set out as a fundraising event to rescue the decaying Towersey Village Memorial Hall \u2013 a building that commemorated the 14 men who had lost their lives in the First World War. In that first year (1965), it was a one-day village fete with morris dancing and a folk singing session in the pub barn. Its success can be measured by the money raised, the enjoyment of the day by the village residents and visitors, and by the fact that, in the following year, a three-day event was held<ref>Writer Derek Schofield reported by Folking.com \u2013 http://folking.com/towersey-festival-50-years-in-the-making/</ref>.\n\nThe festival attracts approximately 10,000 people each year although the 2004 event (26 to 30 August) attracted much higher numbers than ever before. This is partly due to that year being the festival's 40th anniversary.\n\nThe 40th ''Ruby'' festival ran from 26-30 August 2004 and featured appearances from Rory McLeod, Flook and Martin Simpson.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040613180451/http://www.towerseyfestival.com/tartists.html Towersey Festival 13 June 2004 website retrieved via Internet Archive Wayback Time Machine 25 February 2019</ref>\n\nThe venues/ stages in which festival activities take place include The Big Club (formerly known as the Concert Tent); The Festival Dance House (FDH); The Festival Green (formerly known as The Market Square and the Arena); and Venue 65 <ref>Towersey Stages and Venues http://www.towerseyfestival.com/stages-venues/</ref>.  Other features include The Den (for storytelling and spoken word), the craft tent and the craft market, Creative Quarter and dedicated areas for children (5-11yrs) and youth (11yrs+).\n\nRegular performers at Towersey include [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] and [[Les Barker]].  The latter made a live recording there in 1995 while Roy released Live at Towersey Festival 2015 during 2016<ref>Roy Bailey Live at Towersey Festival, at Folk Radio \u2013 http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2016/08/roy-bailey-live-at-towersey/</ref>. A Towersey Festival Patron, Roy performed at the very first festival, and his annual Monday afternoon concerts are greeted by capacity crowds.  [[The Unthanks]] and [[Spiers and Boden|John Spiers and Jon Boden]] had successful performances there in their early careers, while [[Eliza Carthy]] played her first solo show at the festival. Eliza said: \"Towersey gave me my first ever solo gig ... and one of the most memorable gigs of my life; a Chipolata 5 gig so full and rowdy that they had to take the sides of the marquee down.\" <ref>FolkRadioUK, 'Double Celebration for Towersey', 15 May 2014, http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2014/05/double-celebration-for-towersey/</ref>\n\nDiscussing the festival\u2019s appeal and longevity, Roy Bailey stated: \u201cChildren play safely and many lifelong friendships have been developed here. People met here and got married here and generations of families return every year.\u201d<ref>Reported by Folking.com \u2013 http://folking.com/towersey-festival-50-years-in-the-making/</ref>\n\nThe festival's 50th anniversary in 2014 was headlined by [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]]<ref>Oxford Times, Richard Thompson to Headline Towersey Festival (28 Jan 2014) http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/music/10968016.Richard_Thompson_to_headline_Towersey_festival/</ref>. The anniversary was also marked by the publication of a book, ''Towersey Festival: 50 Years In The Making'' which explored the 50 year history of the festival, from its inception to present day. <ref>Folking.com \u2013 Towersey Festival: 50 Years In The Making \u2013 http://folking.com/towersey-festival-50-years-in-the-making/</ref>\n\nSince 2015, the festival has been based at Thame Showground. <ref>http://www.witneygazette.co.uk/news/wgheadlines/11822007.display/</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Towersey Festival is being relocated to the Claydon Estate in Buckinghamshire to allow for expansion and a new programme of outdoor and wellness activities.\n<ref> https://www.towerseyfestival.com </ref>\n\n2019 saw the festival present an exhibition at Thame Museum entitled ''Capturing Towersey: Festival Photographs By Phil Sofer'' - a collection of images shot at the festival by the official festival photographer, Phil Sofer.<ref>[https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17651318.towersey-festival-images-going-on-show-in-thame/ Oxford Mail] Towersey Festival Images Going On Show In Thame, 20 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Recent headliners==\n\n[[File:The_Shires,_Towersey_2018.jpg|The Shires at Towersey 2018|thumb|right]]\n\n'''2012:''' The South, [[Bellowhead]], [[Nic Jones]], Edward II, [[Kathryn Tickell]], [[The Albion Band]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2012/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2012'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2013:''' [[The Unthanks]], [[Show Of Hands]], [[Home Service]], Eliza and Martin Carthy, [[The Blockheads]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2013/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2013'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2014:''' Topic Records 75th Anniversary Concert (featuring [[Norma Waterson]], [[Eliza Carthy]], [[Martin Carthy]] and guests), [[The Bootleg Beatles]], [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]], [[Seth Lakeman]], [[Lau (band)|Lau]], Conservatoire Folk Ensemble <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2014/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2014'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2015:''' Bellowhead, [[Stornoway (band)|Stornoway]], [[Joan Armatrading]], Show Of Hands, [[Martin Simpson|Simpson]] [[Andy Cutting|Cutting]] and [[Nancy Kerr|Kerr]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2015/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2015'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2016:''' [[Billy Bragg]], [[Kate Rusby]], [[The Wonder Stuff]], [[Ukulele Orchestra of Great Britain]], [[9 Bach]], [[Midge Ure]], [[Tom Robinson]], [[The Young'Uns]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2016/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2016'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2017:''' [[Jon Boden]], [[KT Tunstall]], Eliza Carthy and The Wayward Band, [[Newton Faulkner]], Show Of Hands, [[Lindisfarne (band)|Lindisfarne]], Demon Barbers XL, Coope Boyes and Simpson <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2017/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2017'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2018:''' [[The Shires (duo)|The Shires]], [[The Proclaimers]], [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]] Electric Trio, [[Beth Orton]], [[Big Country]], [[Sharon Shannon]] Band, [[Fisherman's Friends]], [[Blair Dunlop]], [[Brighouse and Rastrick Brass Band]], [[Peter Knight (folk musician)|Peter Knight]] and [[John Spiers]]<ref>Oxford Mail, Proclaimers, Beth Orton and Fisherman's Friends announced for Towersey Festival 2018 (7 Feb 2018) \u2013 http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/15925102.Proclaimers_among_headliners_for_Towersey_Festival_2018/</ref> <ref>Oxford Mail, Final Headline Act Announced, 13 March 2018, http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/16083958.Final_headline_act_announced_for_Towersey_Festival/ </ref>\n\n'''2019:''' [[The Selecter]], [[Hothouse Flowers]], [[Newton Faulkner]], [[Seth Lakeman]], [[From The Jam]], [[The Unthanks]], [[Steve Harley]], [[Oysterband]], [[The Bar-Steward Sons of Val Doonican]] and a special tribute to [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] with Tom Robinson, Martin Simpson and guests.<ref>[https://www.thamehub.co.uk/acts-announced-towersey-2019/ 'More Acts Announced For Towersey 2019'] ThameHub, accessed 24 April 2019.</ref>\n\n==Towersey traditions==\n\n[[File:Roy Bailey and band, Towersey 2018.jpg|thumb|[[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] and guests performing at his last Towersey Festival in 2018.]]\n\n[[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]]'s Monday afternoon concert, featuring invited guests, was a Towersey tradition until Bailey's death in 2018.  For the 2019 festival, the organisers announced a celebration of Bailey's life, featuring many of the artists who had played as guests at his concerts.<ref name='2019poster'>{{cite tweet|user=towerseyfesti|number=1111255114122256386|date=28 March 2019|title=We know we've made you wait for this but we are delighted to finally share our full list of #towersey2019 headliners ........|access-date=1 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe festival traditionally ends with a Festival Finale singalong in Venue 65, with the closing act leading the audience in a rendition of [[The Beatles]]' ''[[Hey Jude]]''.<ref>The Albion Band at Towersey 2012, Hey Jude \u2013 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=szNqVQhmfOg</ref>.\n\nMonday evening also sees the festival's traditional Lantern Parade<ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/14710179.Towersey_Festival_will_draw_to_a_close_tonight_with_lantern_parade_and_folk_ensemble/</ref>. The lanterns are made by members of the audience over the duration of the festival.\n\nIn a tradition dating to 1990, many men wear dresses on the last night of the festival. This began as a hen party for a Towersey regular, where the bride agreed that, due to the lack of female friends attending, men could attend if they dressed appropriately. The following year, the bride and groom held a Sunday afternoon [[cocktail party]], before the Sunday evening session in the Barn, with guests asked to wear their wedding outfits. In time, this evolved into 'Dress Up Sunday'. The bride still attends the festival regularly as a steward.\n\n==Towersey releases==\n\nThe festival has released three compilation albums to date. The first was released in 1969, featuring acts recorded live at the 1968 festival, while the next two included (mostly) studio recordings of artists due to appear at the festival that year, and were released via digital distribution platform [[NoiseTrade]].\n\n* '''Festival at Towersey''' (Zeus 1969), 10-track vinyl album featuring [[John Kirkpatrick (musician)|John Kirkpatrick]], The Yetties, Bob Grant and John Graham, Brian Perrett and Dennis Manners.<ref>Mainly Norfolk: English Folk and Other Good Music: Festival at Towersey album \u2013 https://mainlynorfolk.info/john.kirkpatrick/records/festivalattowersey.html</ref>\n\n* '''Towersey Festival 2015''' (NoiseTrade, 2015), free 18 track digital download featuring [[Kim Churchill]], Keston Cobblers' Club, Chris While and Julie matthews, Ninebarrow, The Askew Sisters, [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] [[Martin Simpson]] and [[Andy Cutting]]<ref>NoiseTrade Towersey Festival 2015 \u2013 https://noisetrade.com/towerseyfestival2015/towersey-festival-2015</ref>\n\n* '''Towersey Festival 2016''' (NoiseTrade, 2016), free 18 track digital download featuring [[The Young'uns]], [[Nizlopi]], [[Rory McLeod (singer-songwriter)|Rory McLeod]], [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]], [[The Urban Folk Quartet]]<ref>FolkRadioUK \u2013 http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2016/07/free-download-towersey-festival-album/</ref> <ref>NoiseTrade Towersey Festival 2016 \u2013 https://noisetrade.com/towerseyfestival2015/towersey-festival-2016</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Towersey Festival}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.towerseyfestival.com/}}\n*[http://www.mrscasey.co.uk/ Mrs Casey Music] \u2013 organisers of the festival\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Music festivals in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Folk festivals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1965]]\n[[Category:1965 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = Towersey Festival\n| native_name  =\n| logo         = <!--INCLUDE \"[[File:Filename.ext]]\" when entering file name-->\n| logo_caption =\n| image        = Crowd watching The Proclaimers, Towersey 2018.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = Venue 65, Towersey 2018\n| date         = <!--\"dates=\" also works, as merged from\n                 Template:Infobox festival. Do not use both-->\n| begins       =\n| ends         =\n| prev         = \n| next         = \n| frequency    = Annually\n| location     = [[Thame]], Oxfordshire, England\n| years_active =\n| first        = 1965\n| participants =\n| attendance   = c. 10,000\n| genre        =\n| budget       =\n| patron       =\n| organised    = <!--\"organised=\" also works-->\n| website      = {{URL|towerseyfestival.com/}}\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Towersey Festival''' is an annual festival of [[folk music|folk]], [[world music]] and [[traditional dance]], previously held in the village of [[Towersey]], now relocated <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.towerseyvillage.co.uk/about-towersey-village/history/festival/|title=Towersey Festival \u2013 Towersey Village|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref> to neighbouring [[Thame]] in Oxfordshire, England. It has taken place every August [[bank holiday]] weekend since its founding in 1965.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Towersey_music_festival_(4)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1671760.jpg|thumb|right|Festivalgoers at Towersey Festival 2006]]\n\nThe festival set out as a fundraising event to rescue the decaying Towersey Village Memorial Hall \u2013 a building that commemorated the 14 men who had lost their lives in the First World War. In that first year (1965), it was a one-day village fete with morris dancing and a folk singing session in the pub barn. Its success can be measured by the money raised, the enjoyment of the day by the village residents and visitors, and by the fact that, in the following year, a three-day event was held<ref>Writer Derek Schofield reported by Folking.com \u2013 http://folking.com/towersey-festival-50-years-in-the-making/</ref>.\n\nThe festival attracts approximately 10,000 people each year although the 2004 event (26 to 30 August) attracted much higher numbers than ever before. This is partly due to that year being the festival's 40th anniversary.\n\nThe 40th ''Ruby'' festival ran from 26-30 August 2004 and featured appearances from Rory McLeod, Flook and Martin Simpson.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040613180451/http://www.towerseyfestival.com/tartists.html Towersey Festival 13 June 2004 website retrieved via Internet Archive Wayback Time Machine 25 February 2019</ref>\n\nThe venues/ stages in which festival activities take place include The Big Club (formerly known as the Concert Tent); The Festival Dance House (FDH); The Festival Green (formerly known as The Market Square and the Arena); and Venue 65 <ref>Towersey Stages and Venues http://www.towerseyfestival.com/stages-venues/</ref>.  Other features include The Den (for storytelling and spoken word), the craft tent and the craft market, Creative Quarter and dedicated areas for children (5-11yrs) and youth (11yrs+).\n\nRegular performers at Towersey include [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] and [[Les Barker]].  The latter made a live recording there in 1995 while Roy released Live at Towersey Festival 2015 during 2016<ref>Roy Bailey Live at Towersey Festival, at Folk Radio \u2013 http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2016/08/roy-bailey-live-at-towersey/</ref>. A Towersey Festival Patron, Roy performed at the very first festival, and his annual Monday afternoon concerts are greeted by capacity crowds.  [[The Unthanks]] and [[Spiers and Boden|John Spiers and Jon Boden]] had successful performances there in their early careers, while [[Eliza Carthy]] played her first solo show at the festival. Eliza said: \"Towersey gave me my first ever solo gig ... and one of the most memorable gigs of my life; a Chipolata 5 gig so full and rowdy that they had to take the sides of the marquee down.\" <ref>FolkRadioUK, 'Double Celebration for Towersey', 15 May 2014, http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2014/05/double-celebration-for-towersey/</ref>\n\nDiscussing the festival\u2019s appeal and longevity, Roy Bailey stated: \u201cChildren play safely and many lifelong friendships have been developed here. People met here and got married here and generations of families return every year.\u201d<ref>Reported by Folking.com \u2013 http://folking.com/towersey-festival-50-years-in-the-making/</ref>\n\nThe festival's 50th anniversary in 2014 was headlined by [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]]<ref>Oxford Times, Richard Thompson to Headline Towersey Festival (28 Jan 2014) http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/music/10968016.Richard_Thompson_to_headline_Towersey_festival/</ref>. The anniversary was also marked by the publication of a book, ''Towersey Festival: 50 Years In The Making'' which explored the 50 year history of the festival, from its inception to present day. <ref>Folking.com \u2013 Towersey Festival: 50 Years In The Making \u2013 http://folking.com/towersey-festival-50-years-in-the-making/</ref>\n\nSince 2015, the festival has been based at Thame Showground. <ref>http://www.witneygazette.co.uk/news/wgheadlines/11822007.display/</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Towersey Festival is being relocated to the Claydon Estate in Buckinghamshire to allow for expansion and a new programme of outdoor and wellness activities.\n<ref> https://www.towerseyfestival.com </ref>\n\n2019 saw the festival present an exhibition at Thame Museum entitled ''Capturing Towersey: Festival Photographs By Phil Sofer'' - a collection of images shot at the festival by the official festival photographer, Phil Sofer.<ref>[https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17651318.towersey-festival-images-going-on-show-in-thame/ Oxford Mail] Towersey Festival Images Going On Show In Thame, 20 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Recent Headliners==\n\n[[File:The_Shires,_Towersey_2018.jpg|The Shires at Towersey 2018|thumb|right]]\n\n'''2012:''' The South, [[Bellowhead]], [[Nic Jones]], Edward II, [[Kathryn Tickell]], [[The Albion Band]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2012/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2012'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2013:''' [[The Unthanks]], [[Show Of Hands]], [[Home Service]], Eliza and Martin Carthy, [[The Blockheads]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2013/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2013'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2014:''' Topic Records 75th Anniversary Concert (featuring [[Norma Waterson]], [[Eliza Carthy]], [[Martin Carthy]] and guests), [[The Bootleg Beatles]], [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]], [[Seth Lakeman]], [[Lau (band)|Lau]], Conservatoire Folk Ensemble <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2014/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2014'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2015:''' Bellowhead, [[Stornoway (band)|Stornoway]], [[Joan Armatrading]], Show Of Hands, [[Martin Simpson|Simpson]] [[Andy Cutting|Cutting]] and [[Nancy Kerr|Kerr]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2015/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2015'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2016:''' [[Billy Bragg]], [[Kate Rusby]], [[The Wonder Stuff]], [[Ukulele Orchestra of Great Britain]], [[9 Bach]], [[Midge Ure]], [[Tom Robinson]], [[The Young'Uns]] <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2016/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2016'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2017:''' [[Jon Boden]], [[KT Tunstall]], Eliza Carthy and The Wayward Band, [[Newton Faulkner]], Show Of Hands, [[Lindisfarne (band)|Lindisfarne]], Demon Barbers XL, Coope Boyes and Simpson <ref>[http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/towersey/2017/lineup.shtml 'Towersey Line Up 2017'] eFestivals</ref>\n\n'''2018:''' [[The Shires (duo)|The Shires]], [[The Proclaimers]], [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]] Electric Trio, [[Beth Orton]], [[Big Country]], [[Sharon Shannon]] Band, [[Fisherman's Friends]], [[Blair Dunlop]], [[Brighouse and Rastrick Brass Band]], [[Peter Knight (folk musician)|Peter Knight]] and [[John Spiers]]<ref>Oxford Mail, Proclaimers, Beth Orton and Fisherman's Friends announced for Towersey Festival 2018 (7 Feb 2018) \u2013 http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/15925102.Proclaimers_among_headliners_for_Towersey_Festival_2018/</ref> <ref>Oxford Mail, Final Headline Act Announced, 13 March 2018, http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/16083958.Final_headline_act_announced_for_Towersey_Festival/ </ref>\n\n'''2019:''' [[The Selecter]], [[Hothouse Flowers]], [[Newton Faulkner]], [[Seth Lakeman]], [[From The Jam]], [[The Unthanks]], [[Steve Harley]], [[Oysterband]], [[The Bar-Steward Sons of Val Doonican]] and a special tribute to [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] with Tom Robinson, Martin Simpson and guests.<ref>[https://www.thamehub.co.uk/acts-announced-towersey-2019/ 'More Acts Announced For Towersey 2019'] ThameHub, accessed 24 April 2019.</ref>\n\n==Towersey Traditions==\n\n[[File:Roy Bailey and band, Towersey 2018.jpg|thumb|[[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] and guests performing at his last Towersey Festival in 2018.]]\n\n[[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]]'s Monday afternoon concert, featuring invited guests, was a Towersey tradition until Bailey's death in 2018.  For the 2019 festival, the organisers announced a celebration of Bailey's life, featuring many of the artists who had played as guests at his concerts.<ref name='2019poster'>{{cite tweet|user=towerseyfesti|number=1111255114122256386|date=28 March 2019|title=We know we've made you wait for this but we are delighted to finally share our full list of #towersey2019 headliners ........|access-date=1 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe festival traditionally ends with a Festival Finale singalong in Venue 65, with the closing act leading the audience in a rendition of [[The Beatles]]' ''[[Hey Jude]]''.<ref>The Albion Band at Towersey 2012, Hey Jude \u2013 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=szNqVQhmfOg</ref>.\n\nMonday evening also sees the festival's traditional Lantern Parade<ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/14710179.Towersey_Festival_will_draw_to_a_close_tonight_with_lantern_parade_and_folk_ensemble/</ref>. The lanterns are made by members of the audience over the duration of the festival.\n\nIn a tradition dating to 1990, many men wear dresses on the last night of the festival. This began as a hen party for a Towersey regular, where the bride agreed that, due to the lack of female friends attending, men could attend if they dressed appropriately. The following year, the bride and groom held a Sunday afternoon [[cocktail party]], before the Sunday evening session in the Barn, with guests asked to wear their wedding outfits. In time, this evolved into 'Dress Up Sunday'. The bride still attends the festival regularly as a steward.\n\n==Towersey Releases==\n\nThe festival has released three compilation albums to date. The first was released in 1969, featuring acts recorded live at the 1968 festival, while the next two included (mostly) studio recordings of artists due to appear at the festival that year, and were released via digital distribution platform [[NoiseTrade]].\n\n* '''Festival at Towersey''' (Zeus 1969), 10-track vinyl album featuring [[John Kirkpatrick (musician)|John Kirkpatrick]], The Yetties, Bob Grant and John Graham, Brian Perrett and Dennis Manners.<ref>Mainly Norfolk: English Folk and Other Good Music: Festival at Towersey album \u2013 https://mainlynorfolk.info/john.kirkpatrick/records/festivalattowersey.html</ref>\n\n* '''Towersey Festival 2015''' (NoiseTrade, 2015), free 18 track digital download featuring [[Kim Churchill]], Keston Cobblers' Club, Chris While and Julie matthews, Ninebarrow, The Askew Sisters, [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]] [[Martin Simpson]] and [[Andy Cutting]]<ref>NoiseTrade Towersey Festival 2015 \u2013 https://noisetrade.com/towerseyfestival2015/towersey-festival-2015</ref>\n\n* '''Towersey Festival 2016''' (NoiseTrade, 2016), free 18 track digital download featuring [[The Young'uns]], [[Nizlopi]], [[Rory McLeod (singer-songwriter)|Rory McLeod]], [[Roy Bailey (folk singer)|Roy Bailey]], [[The Urban Folk Quartet]]<ref>FolkRadioUK \u2013 http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2016/07/free-download-towersey-festival-album/</ref> <ref>NoiseTrade Towersey Festival 2016 \u2013 https://noisetrade.com/towerseyfestival2015/towersey-festival-2016</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Towersey Festival}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.towerseyfestival.com/}}\n*[http://www.mrscasey.co.uk/ Mrs Casey Music] \u2013 organisers of the festival\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Music festivals in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Folk festivals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1965]]\n[[Category:1965 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Viennese Waltz", "label": "safe", "comment": "lc", "url_