{"title_page": "V\u0103leni, Neam\u021b", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Neam\u021b\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Neam\u021b County\n|name=V\u0103leni\n|image_map              = V\u0103leni in the Neam\u021b County.svg\n|coordinates = {{coord|47|01|40|N|26|41|15|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''V\u0103leni''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Neam\u021b County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of four villages: David, Moreni, Munteni and V\u0103leni. These were part of [[Bote\u0219ti]] Commune until 2004, when they were split off.\n{{Neam\u0163 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valeni, Neamt}}\n[[Category:Communes in Neam\u021b County]]\n\n{{Neam\u0163-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Neam\u021b\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Neam\u021b County\n|name=V\u0103leni\n|image_map=\n|coordinates = {{coord|47|01|40|N|26|41|15|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''V\u0103leni''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Neam\u021b County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of four villages: David, Moreni, Munteni and V\u0103leni. These were part of [[Bote\u0219ti]] Commune until 2004, when they were split off.\n{{Neam\u0163 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valeni, Neamt}}\n[[Category:Communes in Neam\u021b County]]\n\n{{Neam\u0163-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V%C4%83leni,_Neam%C8%9B"}
{"title_page": "Bildwissenschaft", "text_new": "{{italictitle}}\n'''''Bildwissenschaft''''' is an academic discipline in the [[German-speaking world]]. Similar to [[visual studies]], and defined in relation to [[art history]], ''Bildwissenschaft'' (approximately, \"image-science\") refers to a number of different approaches to images, their interpretation and their social significance. Originating in the early 20th century, the field has become more prominent since the 1990s. In the contemporary period, significant theorists and practitioners of ''Bildwissenschaft'' have included {{ill|Klaus Sachs-Hombach|de}}, [[Gottfried Boehm]], [[Hans Belting]], [[Horst Bredekamp]] and {{ill|Lambert Wiesing|de}}, each of whom have developed distinct orientations toward their subject matter.\n\n==Etymology==\n''[[Wissenschaft]]'' (from ''Wissen'', meaning \"knowledge\") is similar in meaning to \"science\", but is used differently and with different connotations.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}} Whereas \"science\" typically refers specifically to [[empirical]] investigations in the [[natural sciences]] and [[social sciences]], ''Wissenschaft'' does not carry the same methodological implications.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}} Nevertheless, ''Wissenschaft'' is more restrictive than the English \"studies\", as it indicates the systematic ordering of knowledge, that attention be paid to questions of method, and that a discipline aspire to a comprehensive treatment of its subject.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}}\n\nSimilarly, ''[[wikt:Bild#German|Bild]]'' is close in meaning to \"image\", but refers to pictures of all kinds, both representational and abstract, including paintings, drawings, photographs, computer-generated images, film and sculpture; illustrations, figures, maps and diagrams; and [[mental image]]s and metaphors.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}}\n\n==Overview==\n''Bildwissenschaft'' expands the parameters of [[art history]] to encompass, and to take seriously, images of all kinds.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=418}} The polysemic character of the term ''Bild'' has been embraced by proponents of ''Bildwissenschaft'' as a means of encouraging [[interdisciplinarity]] and collaboration.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}} This characteristic also facilitates the avoidance of any distinction between [[high culture]] and [[low culture]].{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|pp=209\u201310}} Accordingly, ''Bildwissenschaft'' incorporates not only the study of \"low culture\" images but also of scientific, architectural and cartographic images and diagrams.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210}}\n\n''Bildwissenschaft'' occupies a more central role in the [[liberal arts]] and [[humanities]] in German-speaking nations than that afforded to art history or [[visual studies]] in the United States and United Kingdom.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=140}} The tendency in the English-speaking world to see art history and visual studies as entirely distinct disciplines has carried over into the German and Austrian context to an extent, and efforts to define ''Bildwissenschaft'' in opposition to art history have been pursued.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=419}}\n\nSignificant differences between ''Bildwissenschaft'' and Anglophone cultural and visual studies include the former's examination of images dating from the [[early modern period]], and its emphasis on continuities over breaks with the past.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=212}} Whereas Anglo-American visual studies can be seen as a continuation of [[critical theory]] in its attempt to reveal power relations, ''Bildwissenschaft'' is not explicitly political.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=213}}\n\n[[Charlotte Klonk]] has argued that ''Bildwissenschaft'' is [[ontological]] rather than historical, concerned with fundamental questions \"of what images are able to achieve in general and what distinguishes them from other vehicles of knowledge.\"{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=143\u20134}} Matthew Rampley describes ''Bildwissenschaft'' as \"a heterogeneous and disunified field that encompasses widely divergent and often competing interests and approaches.\"{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=121}}\n\n==History==\nThe major elements of ''Bildwissenschaft'' were developed in Germany and Austria in the period from 1900 to 1933.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=418}} Art historians including [[Herman Grimm]], [[Wilhelm L\u00fcbke]], [[Anton Heinrich Springer]], [[Jacob Burckhardt]], [[Heinrich W\u00f6lfflin]] and [[Erwin Panofsky]], all of whom saw value in photographs and [[slide show|slides]], contributed to the development of ''Bildwissenschaft''.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=422}} After 1970 it saw a revival and began to incorporate the study of advertising, photography, film and video, [[political symbolism]], [[digital art]] and [[Internet art]].{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=418}} The development of ''Bildwissenschaft'' to an extent paralleled that of the field of visual culture in the United Kingdom and United States.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=121}} Rampley suggests that while the discipline's development can be situated as part of a wider process in Anglophone scholarship, as well as in France, Spain and Italy, such an account is accurate \"only in the most general sense of a shift away from art history as the master discourse governing interpretation and analysis of the image.\"{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=133}}\n\n''Bildwissenschaft'' subsequently influenced the [[structuralism]] of [[Claude L\u00e9vi-Strauss]] and the [[habitus theory]] of [[Pierre Bourdieu]], as well as developments in art history.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=428}}\n\nKlonk argues that the re-emergence of ''Bildwissenschaft'' within art history after 1998 was the result of, first, the contention that the circulation of images in [[mass media]] had the effect of reconfiguring previously text-based societies as image-based societies; second, that the methodologies of the discipline of art history were well-suited to apprehending this new conjuncture; and, third, that art history's focus would of necessity expand to encompass (for example) scientific imagery, advertisements and popular culture.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=142}} Work in ''Bildwissenschaft'' in the 2000s and 2010s has tended to argue that linguistic theories of meaning and interpretation cannot be applied to the visual realm, which has ''[[sui generis]]'' characteristics, and that prevalent approaches to art history unjustifiably prioritise the linguistic over the visual.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=212}}\n\n[[Gilles Deleuze]], [[Aby Warburg]], [[Carl Justi]], [[Carl Schmitt]], [[Pierre Bourdieu]] and [[Paul Feyerabend]] have been identified as precursors of modern ''Bildwissenschaft''.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=121}}\n\nIn 2012, Rampley wrote that ''Bildwissenschaft'' \"is increasingly gaining currency as the denominator of a new set of theoretical discourses\" in the German-speaking world, and had been the subject of several books offering introductions to the field, but emphasised that this was not indicative of \"a single unified field\".{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=134}}\n\n==Theorists and practitioners==\n===Klaus Sachs-Hombach===\nIn the 1990s and 2000s, {{ill|Klaus Sachs-Hombach|de}} used the concept in his discussion of the [[semantics]] and psychology of images, and the possibility in [[semiotics]] of an analogy between images and texts, an analogy he called into question.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|pp=121\u20132}} Sachs-Hombach's conception of ''Bildwissenschaft'' frames the concept in terms of theoretical issues of cognition and models of interpretation.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=123}} His edited volume ''Bildwissenschaft: Disziplinen, Themen, Methoden'' (2005) draws together work by experts across 28 disciplines (including art history) to argue for the possibility of a universal and interdisciplinary ''Bildwissenschaft'' that would function not as a wholly new discipline, but rather as a \"common theoretical framework that could provide an integrative research programme for the various disciplines\".{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210}} Understood in this way, Sachs-Hombach argued that ''Bildwissenschaft'' should integrate and systematise insights from these various bodies of knowledge, analyse and define a set of common basic concepts, and develop strategies for interdisciplinary co-operation.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210\u201311}} Jason Gaiger has argued that Sachs-Hombach's work is the best representation \"of ''Bildwissenschaft'' as an interdisciplinary research project\".{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210}}\n\n===Gottfried Boehm===\n[[Gottfried Boehm]]'s account of the concept drew on [[aesthetics]] and the work of [[Maurice Merleau-Ponty]], [[Hans-Georg Gadamer]], [[Hans Jonas]], [[Arthur Danto]], [[Meyer Schapiro]], [[Kurt Bauch]] and [[Max Imdahl]].{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=123}} Boehm addressed questions around the [[phenomenology]] of viewing and pictorial representation and the question of medium.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=123}} He also sought to understand the cognitive processes involved in the presentation and perception of images, and their differences from linguistic processes.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=143}}\n\n===Hans Belting===\n[[Hans Belting]], in 2001, offered another account, which sought to develop an anthropological theory of the image in order to examines its universal functions that span cultural distinctions, and considered the relationship between the image and the body.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=126}}{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|pp=211\u201312}} Belting examined images used in religious contexts in order to identify the original non-artistic functions of images today considered [[art object]]s, and argued that \"art\" was a unit of analysis had emerged in the 16th century that obstructed corporeal engagements with images.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|pp=126\u20137}} In ''Likeness and Presence'' (1990), Belting argued for the necessity of understanding the ways images give meaning to their contexts, rather than gaining meaning from their contexts, in order to understand images as actors with their own agency.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=143}} Belting argues that art history as a disciplinary formation is outmoded and potentially obsolete,{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=214}} and that a universal ''Bildwissenschaft'', the exact scope and methods of which remain uncertain, should be sought.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=211}}\n\n===Horst Bredekamp===\n[[Horst Bredekamp]]'s 21st-century work considered the cognitive functions performed by the image, the question of a stylistic history of scientific imagery, and the role played by visual argumentation during the [[Scientific Revolution]].{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=130}} Focusing primarily on images that fall outside of art proper, such as those used in the works of the philosophers [[Thomas Hobbes]] and [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz]] and the scientists [[Charles Darwin]] and [[Galileo Galilei]], Bredekamp argues that images inculcate a particular kind of understanding that could not be formed in their absence.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=144}} Bredekamp criticises the idea, associated with Sachs-Hombach, that ''Bildwissenschaft'' might be constructed by amassing the pre-existing insights of various disciplines, arguing that a new science cannot be straightforwardly established through the adding together of existing disciplines.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=211}} Against Sachs-Hombach's argument that art history is one of many disciplines on which ''Bildwissenschaft'' should draw, and Belting's argument that art history is outdated or obsolescent, Bredekamp argues that (Austro-German) art history has always contained an incipiently universal orientation and a focus on non-art images.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=214}}\n\n===Lambert Wiesing===\nThe philosopher {{ill|Lambert Wiesing|de}} shares with Bredekamp the belief that ''Bildwissenschaft''{{'}}s universalism is inherent in art history, but argues that ''Bildwissenschaft'' differentiates itself by virtue of its attention to images ''per se'' rather than specific images or groups of images.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|pp=215\u201316}} Wiesing distinguishes between ''Bildwissenschaft'' and ''{{ill|Bildtheorie|de|Bildwissenschaft#Bildwissenschaft und Bildtheorie}}'' (\"image theory\"), arguing that, while the two are complementary, the former is concerned with specific, concrete images, whereas the latter seeks answers to the question of what an image is.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=217}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1086/376303|first=Horst|last=Bredekamp|authorlink=Horst Bredekamp|title=A Neglected Tradition? Art History as ''Bildwissenschaft''|journal=[[Critical Inquiry]]|volume=29|issue=3|year=2003|pages=418\u2013428|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|first=David|last=Craven|title=The New German Art History: From Ideological Critique and the Warburg Renaissance to the ''Bildwissenschaft'' of the Three Bs|journal=Art in Translation|volume=6|issue=2|year=2014|pages=129\u2013147|doi=10.2752/175613114X13998876655059|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|first=Jason|last=Gaiger|title=The Idea of a Universal ''Bildwissenschaft''|journal=Estetika: The Central European Journal of Aesthetic|volume=LI|issue=2|year=2014|pages=208\u2013229|url=http://aesthetics.ff.cuni.cz/file_download/49|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Matthew|last=Rampley|chapter=Bildwissenschaft: Theories of the Image in German-Language Scholarship|title=Art History and Visual Studies in Europe: Transnational Discourses and National Frameworks|editor1-first=Matthew|editor1-last=Rampley|editor2-first=Thierry|editor2-last=Lenain|editor3-first=Hubert|editor3-last=Locher|editor4-first=Andrea|editor4-last=Pinotti|editor5-first=Charlotte|editor5-last=Schoell-Glass|editor6-first=Kitty|editor6-last=Zijlmans|publisher=[[Brill Publishers]]|year=2012|pages=119\u2013134|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Academic disciplines]]\n[[Category:Art history]]\n[[Category:Interdisciplinary subfields]]\n[[Category:Research in Germany]]\n[[Category:Research in Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{italictitle}}\n'''''Bildwissenschaft''''' is an academic discipline in the [[German-speaking world]]. Similar to [[visual studies]], and defined in relation to [[art history]], ''Bildwissenschaft'' (approximately, \"image-science\") refers to a number of different approaches to images, their interpretation and their social significance. Originating in the early 20th century, the field has become more prominent since the 1990s. In the contemporary period, significant theorists and practitioners of ''Bildwissenschaft'' have included {{ill|Klaus Sachs-Hombach|de}}, [[Gottfried Boehm]], [[Hans Belting]], [[Horst Bredekamp]] and {{ill|Lambert Wiesing|de}}, each of whom have developed distinct orientations toward their subject matter.\n\n==Etymology==\n''[[Wissenschaft]]'' (from ''Wissen'', meaning \"knowledge\") is similar in meaning to \"science\", but is used differently and with different connotations.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}} Whereas \"science\" typically refers specifically to [[empirical]] investigations in the [[natural sciences]] and [[social sciences]], ''Wissenschaft'' does not carry the same methodological implications.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}} Nevertheless, ''Wissenschaft'' is more restrictive than the English \"studies\", as it indicates the systematic ordering of knowledge, that attention be paid to questions of method, and that a discipline aspire to a comprehensive treatment of its subject.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}}\n\nSimilarly, ''[[wikt:Bild#German|Bild]]'' is close in meaning to \"image\", but refers to pictures of all kinds, both representational and abstract, incuding paintings, drawings, photographs, computer-generated images, film and sculpture; illustrations, figures, maps and diagrams; and [[mental image]]s and metaphors.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}}\n\n==Overview==\n''Bildwissenschaft'' expands the parameters of [[art history]] to encompass, and to take seriously, images of all kinds.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=418}} The polysemic character of the term ''Bild'' has been embraced by proponents of ''Bildwissenschaft'' as a means of encouraging [[interdisciplinarity]] and collaboration.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=209}} This characteristic also facilitates the avoidance of any distinction between [[high culture]] and [[low culture]].{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|pp=209\u201310}} Accordingly, ''Bildwissenschaft'' incorporates not only the study of \"low culture\" images but also of scientific, architectural and cartographic images and diagrams.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210}}\n\n''Bildwissenschaft'' occupies a more central role in the [[liberal arts]] and [[humanities]] in German-speaking nations than that afforded to art history or [[visual studies]] in the United States and United Kingdom.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=140}} The tendency in the English-speaking world to see art history and visual studies as entirely distinct disciplines has carried over into the German and Austrian context to an extent, and efforts to define ''Bildwissenschaft'' in opposition to art history have been pursued.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=419}}\n\nSignificant differences between ''Bildwissenschaft'' and Anglophone cultural and visual studies include the former's examination of images dating from the [[early modern period]], and its emphasis on continuities over breaks with the past.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=212}} Whereas Anglo-American visual studies can be seen as a continuation of [[critical theory]] in its attempt to reveal power relations, ''Bildwissenschaft'' is not explicitly political.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=213}}\n\n[[Charlotte Klonk]] has argued that ''Bildwissenschaft'' is [[ontological]] rather than historical, concerned with fundamental questions \"of what images are able to achieve in general and what distinguishes them from other vehicles of knowledge.\"{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=143\u20134}} Matthew Rampley describes ''Bildwissenschaft'' as \"a heterogeneous and disunified field that encompasses widely divergent and often competing interests and approaches.\"{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=121}}\n\n==History==\nThe major elements of ''Bildwissenschaft'' were developed in Germany and Austria in the period from 1900 to 1933.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=418}} Art historians including [[Herman Grimm]], [[Wilhelm L\u00fcbke]], [[Anton Heinrich Springer]], [[Jacob Burckhardt]], [[Heinrich W\u00f6lfflin]] and [[Erwin Panofsky]], all of whom saw value in photographs and [[slide show|slides]], contributed to the development of ''Bildwissenschaft''.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=422}} After 1970 it saw a revival and began to incorporate the study of advertising, photography, film and video, [[political symbolism]], [[digital art]] and [[Internet art]].{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=418}} The development of ''Bildwissenschaft'' to an extent paralleled that of the field of visual culture in the United Kingdom and United States.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=121}} Rampley suggests that while the discipline's development can be situated as part of a wider process in Anglophone scholarship, as well as in France, Spain and Italy, such an account is accurate \"only in the most general sense of a shift away from art history as the master discourse governing interpretation and analysis of the image.\"{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=133}}\n\n''Bildwissenschaft'' subsequently influenced the [[structuralism]] of [[Claude L\u00e9vi-Strauss]] and the [[habitus theory]] of [[Pierre Bourdieu]], as well as developments in art history.{{sfn|Bredekamp|2003|p=428}}\n\nKlonk argues that the re-emergence of ''Bildwissenschaft'' within art history after 1998 was the result of, first, the contention that the circulation of images in [[mass media]] had the effect of reconfiguring previously text-based societies as image-based societies; second, that the methodologies of the discipline of art history were well-suited to apprehending this new conjuncture; and, third, that art history's focus would of necessity expand to encompass (for example) scientific imagery, advertisements and popular culture.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=142}} Work in ''Bildwissenschaft'' in the 2000s and 2010s has tended to argue that linguistic theories of meaning and interpretation cannot be applied to the visual realm, which has ''[[sui generis]]'' characteristics, and that prevalent approaches to art history unjustifiably prioritise the linguistic over the visual.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=212}}\n\n[[Gilles Deleuze]], [[Aby Warburg]], [[Carl Justi]], [[Carl Schmitt]], [[Pierre Bourdieu]] and [[Paul Feyerabend]] have been identified as precursors of modern ''Bildwissenschaft''.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=121}}\n\nIn 2012, Rampley wrote that ''Bildwissenschaft'' \"is increasingly gaining currency as the denominator of a new set of theoretical discourses\" in the German-speaking world, and had been the subject of several books offering introductions to the field, but emphasised that this was not indicative of \"a single unified field\".{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=134}}\n\n==Theorists and practitioners==\n===Klaus Sachs-Hombach===\nIn the 1990s and 2000s, {{ill|Klaus Sachs-Hombach|de}} used the concept in his discussion of the [[semantics]] and psychology of images, and the possibility in [[semiotics]] of an analogy between images and texts, an analogy he called into question.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|pp=121\u20132}} Sachs-Hombach's conception of ''Bildwissenschaft'' frames the concept in terms of theoretical issues of cognition and models of interpretation.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=123}} His edited volume ''Bildwissenschaft: Disziplinen, Themen, Methoden'' (2005) draws together work by experts across 28 disciplines (including art history) to argue for the possibility of a universal and interdisciplinary ''Bildwissenschaft'' that would function not as a wholly new discipline, but rather as a \"common theoretical framework that could provide an integrative research programme for the various disciplines\".{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210}} Understood in this way, Sachs-Hombach argued that ''Bildwissenschaft'' should integrate and systematise insights from these various bodies of knowledge, analyse and define a set of common basic concepts, and develop strategies for interdisciplinary co-operation.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210\u201311}} Jason Gaiger has argued that Sachs-Hombach's work is the best representation \"of ''Bildwissenschaft'' as an interdisciplinary research project\".{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=210}}\n\n===Gottfried Boehm===\n[[Gottfried Boehm]]'s account of the concept drew on [[aesthetics]] and the work of [[Maurice Merleau-Ponty]], [[Hans-Georg Gadamer]], [[Hans Jonas]], [[Arthur Danto]], [[Meyer Schapiro]], [[Kurt Bauch]] and [[Max Imdahl]].{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=123}} Boehm addressed questions around the [[phenomenology]] of viewing and pictorial representation and the question of medium.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=123}} He also sought to understand the cognitive processes involved in the presentation and perception of images, and their differences from linguistic processes.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=143}}\n\n===Hans Belting===\n[[Hans Belting]], in 2001, offered another account, which sought to develop an anthropological theory of the image in order to examines its universal functions that span cultural distinctions, and considered the relationship between the image and the body.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=126}}{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|pp=211\u201312}} Belting examined images used in religious contexts in order to identify the original non-artistic functions of images today considered [[art object]]s, and argued that \"art\" was a unit of analysis had emerged in the 16th century that obstructed corporeal engagements with images.{{sfn|Rampley|2012|pp=126\u20137}} In ''Likeness and Presence'' (1990), Belting argued for the necessity of understanding the ways images give meaning to their contexts, rather than gaining meaning from their contexts, in order to understand images as actors with their own agency.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=143}} Belting argues that art history as a disciplinary formation is outmoded and potentially obsolete,{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=214}} and that a universal ''Bildwissenschaft'', the exact scope and methods of which remain uncertain, should be sought.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=211}}\n\n===Horst Bredekamp===\n[[Horst Bredekamp]]'s 21st-century work considered the cognitive functions performed by the image, the question of a stylistic history of scientific imagery, and the role played by visual argumentation during the [[Scientific Revolution]].{{sfn|Rampley|2012|p=130}} Focusing primarily on images that fall outside of art proper, such as those used in the works of the philosophers [[Thomas Hobbes]] and [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz]] and the scientists [[Charles Darwin]] and [[Galileo Galilei]], Bredekamp argues that images inculcate a particular kind of understanding that could not be formed in their absence.{{sfn|Craven|2014|p=144}} Bredekamp criticises the idea, associated with Sachs-Hombach, that ''Bildwissenschaft'' might be constructed by amassing the pre-existing insights of various disciplines, arguing that a new science cannot be straightforwardly established through the adding together of existing disciplines.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=211}} Against Sachs-Hombach's argument that art history is one of many disciplines on which ''Bildwissenschaft'' should draw, and Belting's argument that art history is outdated or obsolescent, Bredekamp argues that (Austro-German) art history has always contained an incipiently universal orientation and a focus on non-art images.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=214}}\n\n===Lambert Wiesing===\nThe philosopher {{ill|Lambert Wiesing|de}} shares with Bredekamp the belief that ''Bildwissenschaft''{{'}}s universalism is inherent in art history, but argues that ''Bildwissenschaft'' differentiates itself by virtue of its attention to images ''per se'' rather than specific images or groups of images.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|pp=215\u201316}} Wiesing distinguishes between ''Bildwissenschaft'' and ''{{ill|Bildtheorie|de|Bildwissenschaft#Bildwissenschaft und Bildtheorie}}'' (\"image theory\"), arguing that, while the two are complementary, the former is concerned with specific, concrete images, whereas the latter seeks answers to the question of what an image is.{{sfn|Gaiger|2014|p=217}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1086/376303|first=Horst|last=Bredekamp|authorlink=Horst Bredekamp|title=A Neglected Tradition? Art History as ''Bildwissenschaft''|journal=[[Critical Inquiry]]|volume=29|issue=3|year=2003|pages=418\u2013428|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|first=David|last=Craven|title=The New German Art History: From Ideological Critique and the Warburg Renaissance to the ''Bildwissenschaft'' of the Three Bs|journal=Art in Translation|volume=6|issue=2|year=2014|pages=129\u2013147|doi=10.2752/175613114X13998876655059|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|first=Jason|last=Gaiger|title=The Idea of a Universal ''Bildwissenschaft''|journal=Estetika: The Central European Journal of Aesthetic|volume=LI|issue=2|year=2014|pages=208\u2013229|url=http://aesthetics.ff.cuni.cz/file_download/49|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Matthew|last=Rampley|chapter=Bildwissenschaft: Theories of the Image in German-Language Scholarship|title=Art History and Visual Studies in Europe: Transnational Discourses and National Frameworks|editor1-first=Matthew|editor1-last=Rampley|editor2-first=Thierry|editor2-last=Lenain|editor3-first=Hubert|editor3-last=Locher|editor4-first=Andrea|editor4-last=Pinotti|editor5-first=Charlotte|editor5-last=Schoell-Glass|editor6-first=Kitty|editor6-last=Zijlmans|publisher=[[Brill Publishers]]|year=2012|pages=119\u2013134|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Academic disciplines]]\n[[Category:Art history]]\n[[Category:Interdisciplinary subfields]]\n[[Category:Research in Germany]]\n[[Category:Research in Austria]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEtymology:clean up,typo(s) fixed: incuding \u2192 including", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bildwissenschaft"}
